fness coefficient (cubic term),\n- \\( c \\) is the damping coefficient.\n\nThis form captures:\n- Linear restoring force proportional to position,\n- Nonlinear restoring force proportional to cubic power of position,\n- Damping proportional to velocity.\n\n---\n\n### Updated `equation_v1` function skeleton:\n\n```python\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """Improved version of `equation_v0`.\n\n    Models acceleration in a nonlinear harmonic oscillator with damping.\n\n    y = params[0] + params[1]*x0 + params[2]*x0**3 + params[3]*x1\n\n    Parameters:\n    - params (np.ndarray): Trainable coefficients [offset, linear stiffness, nonlinear stiffness, damping]\n    """\n    return params[0] + params[1] * x0 + params[2] * (x0 ** 3) + params[3] * x1\n```\n\n---\n\nThis skeleton allows learning or fitting parameters for offset, linear and nonlinear stiffness, and damping. You can extend it further by adding higher order terms or other nonlinearities if needed.', 'Given the physical context of a nonlinear harmonic oscillator, the acceleration \\( y \\) (second derivative of position) typically depends on position \\( x_0 \\) and velocity \\( x_1 \\), often including nonlinear terms such as cubic position terms and possibly velocity-dependent damping.\n\nA common form for a nonlinear oscillator acceleration is:\n\n\\[\ny = -k_1 x_0 - k_2 x_0^3 - c x_1\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( k_1 \\) is the linear stiffness coefficient,\n- \\( k_2 \\) is the nonlinear stiffness coefficient,\n- \\( c \\) is the damping coefficient.\n\nWe can represent this in a parameterized skeleton function with trainable parameters.\n\n---\n\nHere is an improved version of `equation_v1` that includes these terms:\n\n```python\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """Improved version of `equation_v0`.\n\n    Models acceleration in a nonlinear harmonic oscillator with linear and cubic stiffness and linear